</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We continue to experience strong demand for our Paychex HR Services, our largest HRS revenue stream, as evidenced by the continued double-digit growth in client worksite employees.&nbsp;&nbsp;During both fiscal 2016 and fiscal 2015, the PEO, in particular, experienced strong demand.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Retirement services revenue growth was tempered in fiscal 2016 by a lower average asset value of participants&#x2019; funds, offset somewhat by higher basis points earned from external fund managers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Retirement services revenue for fiscal 2015 compared to fiscal 2014 benefited from pricing and higher average asset value of participants&#x2019; funds.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Insurance services revenue growth for both fiscal 2016 and 2015 benefited from growth in our full-service ACA product.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, higher average premiums and clients in our workers&#x2019; compensation product positively impacted revenue in both years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our HR administration products, including time and attendance and HR management, contributed to growth through strong sales of our SaaS solutions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Time and attendance solutions benefited from a small business acquisition in fiscal 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Total service revenue:&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Total service revenue increased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	% for fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and 9% for fiscal 2015, attributable to the factors previously discussed.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	% for fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	increased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	% for fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>

	.&nbsp;&nbsp;For fiscal 201
</FONT>

	6
</FONT>

	, the increase was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	primarily
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	due to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	higher average interest rates and slightly higher average investment balances
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;For fiscal 2015, the increase was primarily due to an increase in average investment balances, while average interest rates earned were flat.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	and 3% for fiscal 2015.&nbsp;

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The net increase in average investment balances for fiscal 2016 was mainly due to client base growth and wage inflation, partially offset by lower state unemployment insurance rates.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The increase in average investment balances for fiscal 2015 was mainly driven by increases in client base and wage inflation.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Total expenses increased 7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	% for fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and 10% for fiscal 2015.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	F
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	iscal 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	impacted by costs relating to the new minimum premium plan health insurance offering within our PEO,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	introduced in January 2014,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	which contributed three percentage points of the increase in total expenses for fiscal 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The increases in total expenses were driven largely by growth in compensation-related expenses.&nbsp;&nbsp;For fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, compensation-related expenses increased due to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	higher wages and performance-based compensation costs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	For fiscal 2015, compensation-related expenses increased due to higher sales headcount and variable costs resulting from strong sales execution, along with higher employee-benefit-related costs, primarily medical expenses.&nbsp;&nbsp;As of May&nbsp;31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016, we had approximately 13,5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	00 employees, compared with
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	13,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	employees as of May&nbsp;31, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Depreciation expense is primarily related to buildings, furniture and fixtures, data processing equipment, and software. Amortization of intangible assets is primarily related to client list acquisitions, which are amortized using either straight-line or a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ccelerated methods.&nbsp;&nbsp;The higher growth rate for depreciation and amortization in fiscal 2016 was primarily driven by higher depreciation related to an increase in internally developed software that was placed in service.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Other expenses include items such as non-capital equipment, delivery, forms and supplies, communications, travel and entertainment, professional services, and other costs incurred to support our business.&nbsp;&nbsp;Other expenses increased due to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	growth within the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	PEO.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, continued investment in product development and supporting technology impacted other expense growth for both fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Operating income:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating income increased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	% for fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and 7% for fiscal 2015. The fluctuations in operating income were attributable to the factors previously discussed.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Operating income, net of certain items is a non-GAAP measure.&nbsp;&nbsp;Refer to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#x201C;Non-GAAP Financial Measure&#x201D; discussion that follows
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Operating income, net of certain items, as a percentage of service revenue was approximately 38% for each of the f
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	iscal years 2016, 2015 and 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;">
	Non-GAAP Financial Measure:&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	In addition to reporting operating income, a U.S. generally accepted accounting principle (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) measure, we present operating income, net of certain items, which is a non-GAAP measure. We believe operating income, net of certain items, is an appropriate additional measure, as it is an indicator of our core business operations performance period over period. It is also the basis of the measure used internally for establishing the following year&#x2019;s targets and measuring management&#x2019;s performance in connection with certain performance-based compensation payments and awards. Operating income, net of certain items, excludes interest on funds held for clients. Interest on funds held for clients is an adjustment to operating income due to the volatility of interest rates, which are not within the control of management. Operating income, net of certain items, is not calculated through the application of GAAP and is not the required form of disclosure by the Securities and Exchange Commission
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	(&#x201C;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	SEC&#x201D;). As such, it should not be considered as a substitute for the GAAP measure of operating income and, therefore, should not be used in isolation, but in conjunction with the GAAP measure. The use of any non-GAAP measure may produce results that vary from the GAAP measure and may not be comparable to a similarly defined non-GAAP measure used by other companies.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Investment income, net:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Investment income, net, primarily represents earnings from our cash and cash equivalents and investments in available-for-sale securities. Investment income does not include interest on funds held for clients, which is included in total revenue. Investment income, net,

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	de
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	creased

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	28

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	balances,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	partially offset by higher

	average
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	interest rate
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	s earned
</FONT>

	.&nbsp;&nbsp;The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	decrease
</FONT>

	in average investment balances for fiscal 201
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Income taxes:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Our effective income tax rate was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	34
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.3% for fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	compared to 36.3% for fiscal 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	36.5% for fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The decrease in the effective income tax rate for fiscal 2016 is related primarily to a net tax benefit that was recorded for income derived in prior tax years from customer-facing software we produced. During the first quarter, we engaged tax specialists to assess the qualification of such software for the Federal &#x201C;Qualified Production Activities Deduction.&#x201D;&nbsp; Based on this assessment, we concluded that certain of our software offerings qualified for this tax deduction in prior tax years and, therefore, we recorded the tax benefits and related tax reserves as a discrete item in the first quarter.&nbsp; Excluding this net tax benefit, the effective income tax rate would have been approximately 35.8% for fiscal 2016.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Refer to Note&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	J
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of the Notes to Co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	nsolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	contained in Item&nbsp;8 of this Form&nbsp;10-K for additional disclosures on income taxes.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our credit facilities are evidenced by promissory notes and are secured by separate pledge security agreements by and between Paychex, Inc. and each of the financial institutions (the &#x201C;Lenders&#x201D;), pursuant to which we have granted each of the Lenders a security interest in certain of our investment securities accounts. The collateral is maintained in a pooled custody account pursuant to the terms of a control agreement and is to be administered under an intercreditor agreement among the Lenders. Under certain circumstances, individual Lenders may require that collateral be transferred from the pooled account into segregated accounts for the benefit of such individual Lenders.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The primary uses of the lines of credit would be to meet short-term funding requirements related to deposit account overdrafts and client fund obligations arising from electronic payment transactions on behalf of our clients in the ordinary course of business, if necessary. No amounts were outstanding against these lines of credit during fiscal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	or as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	May&nbsp;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Certain of the financial institutions are also parties to our credit facility and irrevocable standby letters of credit, which are discussed below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	entered into a committed, unsecured, five-year syndicated credit facility, expiring on August 5, 2020.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the credit f
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	acility, Paychex of New York LLC
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	(the &#x201C;Borrower&#x201D;) may, subject to certain restrictions, borrow up to $1 billion to meet short-term funding requirements.&nbsp;&nbsp;The obligations under this facility have been guaranteed by the Company and certain of its subsidiaries.&nbsp;&nbsp;The outstanding obligations under this credit facility will bear interest at competitive rates to be elected by the Borrower.&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon expiration of the commitment in August 2020, any borrowings outstanding will mature and be payable on such date.&nbsp;&nbsp;This agreement supersedes the $750 million credit facility agreement set to expire on June&nbsp;21, 2018, which was terminated as part of the new agreement.
</FONT>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	subsequently borrowed $100 million for one day under this line in June 2016.
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The credit facility contains various financial and operational covenants that are usual and customary for such arrangements.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Borrower was in compliance with these covenants during fiscal 2016.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 12PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Certain lenders under this credit facility, and their respective affiliates, have performed, and may in the future perform for us, various commercial banking, investment banking, underwriting, and other financial advisory services, for which they have received, and will continue to receive in the future, customary fees and expenses.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million

	to finance working capital needs and for general corporate purposes.&nbsp;

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The obligations under this facility have been guaranteed by the Company and certain of its subsidiaries.&nbsp;&nbsp;The outstanding obligations under this credit facility will bear interest at competitive rates to be elected by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Paychex Advance

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	n March 2019

	, any borrowings outstanding will mature and be payable on such date.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The liability for uncertain tax positions, including interest and net of federal benefits, was approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$54.2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million as of

	May&nbsp;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. Refer to Note
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	J
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of the Notes to Co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	nsolidated Financial Statements

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	contai

	ned in Item&nbsp;8 of this Form 10-K
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	for more information on income taxes. We are not able to reasonably estimate the timing of future cash flows related to this liability and have excluded it from the table above.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Certain deferred compensation plan obligations and other long-term liabilities reported in our Consolidated Balance Sheets amounting to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$68.3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million are excluded from the table above because the timing of actual payments cannot be specifically or reasonably determined due to the variability in assumptions required to project the timing of future payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Advantage Payroll Services Inc. (&#x201C;Advantage&#x201D;) has license agreements with independently owned associate offices (&#x201C;Associates&#x201D;), which are responsible for selling and marketing Advantage Payroll Services
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:5PT;VERTICAL-ALIGN:SUPER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%">
	&#xAE;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and performing certain operational functions, while Paychex and Advantage provide all centralized back-office payroll processing and payroll tax administration services. Under these arrangements, Advantage pays the Associates commissions based on processing activity for the related clients. When we acquired Advantage, there were fifteen Associates. Over the past few years, arrangements with some Associates have been discontinued, and there are currently fewer than ten Associates. Since the actual amounts of future payments are uncertain, obligations under these arrangements are not included in the table above. Commission expense for the Associates for fiscal years
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$16.1 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, $15.1million, and $14.4 million, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In the normal course of business, we make representations and warranties that guarantee the performance of services under service arrangements with clients. Historically, there have been no material losses related to such guarantees. In addition, we have entered into indemnification agreements with our officers and directors, which require us to defend and, if necessary, indemnify these individuals for certain pending or future legal claims as they relate to their services provided to us.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We currently self-insure the deductible portion of various insured exposures under certain employee benefit plans. Our estimated loss exposure under these insurance arrangements is recorded in other current liabilities on our Consolidated Balance Sheets. Historically, the amounts accrued have not been material and are not material as of the reporting date. We also maintain insurance coverage in addition to our purchased primary insurance policies for gap coverage for employment practices liability, errors and omissions, warranty liability, theft and embezzlement, cyber threats, and acts of terrorism; and capacity for deductibles and self-insured retentions through our captive insurance company.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Off-Balance Sheet Arrangements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	As part of our ongoing business, we do not participate in transactions with unconsolidated entities which would have been established for the purpose of facilitating off-balance sheet arrangements or other limited purposes. We do maintain investments as a limited partner in low-income housing projects that are not considered part of our ongoing operations. These investments are accounted for under the equity method of accounting and are less than 1% of our total assets as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	May&nbsp;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The increase in our operating cash flows for fiscal 2016 compared to fiscal 2015 is primarily the result of higher net income, adjusted for non-cash items, along with the positive impact from fluctuations in our oper
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ating assets and liabilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase for fiscal 2015 compared to fiscal 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	is primarily the result of higher net income, adjusted for non-cash items,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	offset by the decrease in cash provided by changes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in our oper
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ating assets and liabilities.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Non-cash adjustments to net income increased for both fiscal 2016 and fiscal 2015, compared to the respective prior year periods
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase in non-cash adjustments for fiscal 2016 was largely due to higher depreciation expense related to an increase in internally developed software placed in service, and an increase in the deferred tax provision.&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase in non-cash adjustments for fiscal 2015 was largely due to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	higher amortization of premiums on available-for-sale securities as the Company has increased its holdings of longer-duration investments, and higher stock-based compensation costs.&nbsp;&nbsp;The fluctuations in our operating assets and liabilities between
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	all
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	periods were primarily related to the timing of collections from clients and payments for compensation, PEO payroll, income tax, and other liabilities.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Funds held for clients and corporate investments:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Funds held for clients consist of short-term funds and available-for-sale securities. Corporate investments are primarily comprised of available-for-sale securities. The portfolio of funds held for clients and corporate investments is detailed in Note&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	F
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of the Notes to Co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	nsolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	contained in Item&nbsp;8 of this Form&nbsp;10-K.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Fluctuations in the net change in funds held for clients and corporate investment activities are largely due to timing within the client funds portfolio.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	For fiscal 2016 compared to fiscal 2015, there was a significant fluctuation due to timing of the day of the week for fiscal year-end.&nbsp;&nbsp;There were larger cash outflows on Tuesday, May 31, 2016 that required the liquidation of funds held in the funds held for clients portfolio.&nbsp;&nbsp;This resulted in positive cash flow from investing activities for fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our net cash
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	inflow
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	from funds held for clients and corporate investment activities for fiscal 2016 was partially offset by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the change in mix of investments with more invested in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	VRDN securities
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and less in cash equivalents as of May 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;For fiscal 2015 compared to fiscal 2014, there was not a significant fluctuation due to timing of the day of the week for fiscal year-end.&nbsp;&nbsp;The net cash outflow position for both fiscal 2015 and fiscal 2014 is related to more purchases of short-term and available-for-sale securities resulting from higher average collections from clients.&nbsp;&nbsp;See further discussion of this timing in the financing cash flows discussion of net change in client fund obligations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In general, fluctuations in net funds held for clients and corporate investment activities primarily relate to timing of purchases, sales, or maturities of investments. The amount of funds held for clients will vary based upon the timing of collection of client funds, and the related remittance of funds to applicable tax or regulatory agencies for payroll tax administration services and to employees of clients utilizing employee payment services.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additional discussion of interest rates and related risks is included in th
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	e &#x201C;Market Risk Factors&#x201D; section
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	contained in Item&nbsp;7A of this Form&nbsp;10-K.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">

</FONT>

	2014

	, we purchased

	approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$4.9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million,

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

	$6.9

	million, respectively, of data processing equipment and software from EMC Corporation. The Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer of EMC Corporation is a member of our Board of Directors (the &#x201C;Board&#x201D;).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Net change in client fund obligations:&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The client fund obligations liability will vary based on the timing of collecting client funds, and the related required remittance of funds to applicable tax or regulatory agencies for payroll tax administration services and to employees of clients utilizing employee payment services. Collections from clients are typically remitted from one to 30 days after receipt, with some items extending to 90 days.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

	23

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#PAYX-20160531X10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Fluctuations in net change in client fund obligations for the years presented are primarily the result of timing of collections and remittances and overall trends in client fund balances.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Timing for fiscal 2016 resulted in a net cash outflow position.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;May 31, 2016 was a Tuesday, a larger cash outflow day due to clearing of Readychex and tax payments.&nbsp;&nbsp;As May 31, 2015 was a Sunday
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, cash on hand would have been higher
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result, there was a net cash outflow over the period in fiscal 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	May 31, 2015 fell on a Sunday, while May 31, 2014 fell on a Saturday.&nbsp;&nbsp;Friday is a large cash outflow day for direct deposit funds, partially offset by tax payment funds collected on that day.&nbsp;&nbsp;This impact was consistent and did not impact the net cash flow position for client funds obligations reflected in fiscal 2015 or fiscal 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;The net cash inflow position in those years is the result of growth in average client funds held.&nbsp;&nbsp;The slight decrease in net cash inflows for fiscal 2015 was the result of lower cash collections for state unemployment insurance with many states lowering their rates early in calendar 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Critical Accounting Policies
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Note&nbsp;A of the Notes to Co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	nsolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	contained in Item&nbsp;8 of th
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	is Form&nbsp;10-K
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	discusses the significant accounting policies of Paychex. Our discussion and analysis of our financial condition and results of operations are based upon our consolidated financial statements, which have been prepared in accordance with U.S. GAAP. The preparation of these financial statements requires us to make estimates, judgments, and assumptions that affect reported amounts of assets, liabilities, revenue, and expenses. On an ongoing basis, we evaluate the accounting policies and estimates used to prepare the consolidated financial statements. We base our estimates on historical experience, future expectations, and assumptions believed to be reasonable under current facts and circumstances. Actual amounts and results could differ from these estimates. Certain accounting policies that are deemed critical to our results of operations or financial position are discussed below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Revenue recognition:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Service revenue is recognized in the period services are rendered and earned under service arrangements with clients where service fees are fixed or determinable and collectability is reasonably assured. Certain processing services are provided under annual service arrangements with revenue recognized ratably over the service period. Our service revenue is largely attributable to processing services where the fee is based on a fixed amount per processing period or a fixed amount per processing period plus a fee per employee or transaction processed.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Fees earned for funding of temporary staffing clients&#x2019; payrolls via purchase of accounts receivable are based on a percentage of funding amounts as specified in the client contract.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The revenue earned from delivery service for the distribution of certain client payroll checks and reports is included in service revenue, and the costs for delivery are included in operating expenses on the Consolidated Statements of Income and Comprehensive Income.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	24
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
</HR>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage27"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#PAYX-20160531X10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	For certain of our service offerings, we receive advance payments for set-up fees from our clients. We defer revenue associated with these advance payments and the related costs, recognizing the revenue and related expenses over the expected life of clients.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	PEO revenue is included in service revenue and is reported net of certain direct pass-through costs billed and incurred, which include wages, taxes,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and certain benefit premiums.&nbsp;&nbsp;D
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	irect costs related to certain benefit plans where the Company retains risk
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	are
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	classified as operating expenses rather than as a reduction in service revenue.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Interest on funds held for clients is earned primarily on funds that are collected from clients before due dates for payroll tax administration services and for employee payment services, and invested until remittance to the applicable tax or regulatory agencies or client employees. These collections from clients are typically remitted from one to 30&nbsp;days after receipt, with some items extending to 90&nbsp;days. The interest earned on these funds is included in total revenue on the Consolidated Statements of Income and Comprehensive Income because the collecting, holding, and remitting of these funds are critical components of providing these services. Interest on funds held for clients also includes net realized gains and losses from the sales of available-for-sale securities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	PEO insurance reserves:&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;As part of the PEO service, we offer workers&#x2019; compensation insurance and health insurance to client companies for the benefit of client employees.&nbsp; Workers' compensation insurance is provided under a fully insured high deductible workers&#x2019; compensation policy with a national insurance carrier. Workers&#x2019; compensation insurance reserves are established to provide for the estimated costs of paying claims up to per occurrence liability limits. In establishing the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	PEO
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	workers' compensation insurance reserves, we use an independent actuarial estimate of undiscounted future cash payments that would be made to settle the claims.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Estimating the ultimate cost of future claims is an uncertain and complex process based upon historical loss experience and actuarial loss projections, and is subject to change due to multiple factors, including economic trends, changes in legal liability law, and damage awards, all of which could materially impact the reserves as reported in the consolidated financial statements. Accordingly, workers' compensation final claim settlements may vary from the present estimates, particularly when those payments may not occur until well into the future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	With respect to our PEO health insurance, we offer various health insurance plans that take the form of either fully insured fixed cost plans with various national insurance carriers or a fully insured minimum premium insurance arrangement with coverage provided through a single national carrier. Under the minimum premium arrangement, our health benefits insurance reserves are established to provide for the payment of claims liability charges in accordance with our service contract with the carrier. The claims liability charges include estimates for reported losses, plus amounts for those claims incurred but not reported, and estimates of certain expenses associated with processing and settling the claims.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We regularly review the adequacy of our estimated insurance reserves. Adjustments to previously established reserves are reflected in the results of operations for the period in which the adjustment is identified. Such adjustments could possibly be significant, reflecting any
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	combination
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of new and adverse or favorable trends.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Goodwill and other intangible assets:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Goodwill is not amortized, but instead is tested for impairment on an annual basis and between annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change in a way to indicate that there has been a potential decline in the fair value of the reporting unit.&nbsp; We performed our annual impairment testing in our fiscal fourth quarter.&nbsp; A quantitative analysis was performed for our German
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	reporting
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	unit.&nbsp; For all other reporting units, we utilized a qualitative assessment to determine if it is more-likely-than-not that the fair value of the reporting unit had declined below its carrying value.&nbsp; The assessment considered various financial, macroeconomic, industry, and reporting unit specific qualitative factors.&nbsp; Based on the results of our testing, no impairment loss was recognized in the results of operations for fiscal years 2016, 2015, or 2014.&nbsp; Subsequent to this review, there have been no events or circumstances that indicate any potential impairment of our goodwill balance
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We also test intangible assets for potential impairment when events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying value may not be recoverable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	25

<A NAME="eolPage28"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#PAYX-20160531X10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Stock-based compensation costs:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;All stock-based awards to employees, including grants of stock options, are recognized as compensation costs in our consolidated financial statements based on their fair values measured as of the date of grant. We estimate the fair value of stock option grants using a Black-Scholes option pricing model. This model requires various assumptions as inputs including expected volatility of the Paychex stock price and expected option life. We estimate volatility based on a combination of historical volatility using stock prices over a period equal to the expected option life and implied market volatility. Expected option life is estimated based on historical exercise behavior.&nbsp;&nbsp;We periodically reassess our assumptions as well as our choice of valuation model, and will reconsider use of this model if additional information becomes available in the future indicating that another model would provide a more accurate estimate of fair value, or if characteristics of future grants would warrant such a change.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We are required to estimate forfeitures and only record compensation costs for those awards that are expected to vest. Our assumptions for forfeitures were determined based on type of award and historical experience. Forfeiture assumptions are adjusted at the point in time a significant change is identified, with any adjustment recorded in the period of change, and the final adjustment at the end of the requisite service period to equal actual forfeitures.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The assumptions of volatility, expected option life, and forfeitures all require significant judgment and are subject to change in the future due to factors such as employee exercise behavior, stock price trends, and changes to type or provisions of stock-based awards. Any change in one or more of these assumptions could have a material impact on the estimated fair value of a future award.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Refer to Note
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	E
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of the Notes to Co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	nsolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	contai
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ned in Item&nbsp;8 of this Form 10-K
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	for further discussion of&nbsp;our stock-based compensation plans.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Income taxes:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;We account for deferred taxes by recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the consolidated financial statements or tax returns. Under this method, deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the difference between the financial statement and tax basis of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse. We record a deferred tax asset related to the stock-based compensation costs recognized for certain sto
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ck-based awards. At the time
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	non-qualified stock options are exercised or stock awards vest, we account for the resulting tax deduction by reducing our accrued income tax liability with an offset to the deferred tax asset and any excess of the tax benefit over the deferred tax asset as an increase to additional paid-in capital. We currently have a sufficient pool of excess tax benefits in additional paid-in capital to absorb any deficiency in tax benefits that fall short of the related deferred tax asset related to stock-based awards.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We maintain a reserve for uncertain tax positions.&nbsp;We evaluate tax positions taken or expected to be taken in a tax return for recognition in our consolidated financial statements. Prior to recording the related tax benefit in our consolidated financial statements,&nbsp;we must conclude that tax positions will be more-likely-than-not to be sustained, assuming those positions will be examined by taxing authorities with full knowledge of all relevant information. The benefit recognized in our consolidated financial statements is the amount&nbsp;we expect to realize after examination by taxing authorities. If a tax position drops below the more-likely-than-not standard, the benefit can no longer be recognized. Assumptions, judgment, and the use of estimates are required in determining if the more-likely-than-not standard has been met when developing the provision for income taxes and in determining the expected benefit. A change in the assessment of the more-likely-than-not standard could materially impact our results of operations or financial position.&nbsp;Refer to Note
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	J
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of the Notes to Co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	nsolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	contained in Item&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	8 of this Form 10-K
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	for further discussion of&nbsp;our reserve for uncertain tax positions
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<EFX_MARKET_RISK>
<A NAME="FIS_MARKET_RISK"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	Ite
</FONT>
<A NAME="PAYX-20160531X10K_HTM_MARKETRISK">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	m&nbsp;7A.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;">
	Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures About Market Risk
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:8PT 0PT 0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Market Risk Factors
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Changes in interest rates and interest rate risk:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Funds held for clients are primarily comprised of short-term funds and available-for-sale securities. Corporate investments are primarily comprised of available-for-sale securities. As a result of our investing activities, we are exposed to changes in interest rates that may materially affect our results of operations and financial position. Changes in interest rates will impact the earnings potential of future investments and will cause fluctuations in the fair value of our longer-term available-for-sale securities. We follow an investment strategy of protecting principal and optimizing liquidity. A substantial portion of our portfolios is invested in high credit quality securities with AAA and AA ratings and A-1/P-1 ratings on short-term securities. We invest predominately in municipal bonds&nbsp;including general obligation bonds, pre-refunded bonds that are secured by a U.S. government escrow, and essential services revenue bonds
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, along with U.S. government agency securities and corporate bonds
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. We limit the amounts that can be invested in any single issuer and invest primarily in short- to intermediate-term instruments whose fair value is less sensitive to interest rate changes. We manage the available-for-sale securities to a benchmark duration of two and one-half to three and three-quarters years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	During fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, our primary short-term investment vehicles were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	bank demand deposit accounts, VRDNs,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	high-quality commercial paper, and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	government agency discount notes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. We have no exposure to high-risk or illiquid investments.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have insignificant exposure to European investments. We have not and do not utilize derivative financial instruments to manage our interest rate risk.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	During fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, the average interest rate earned on our combined funds held for clients and corporate investment portfolios was 1.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	%,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	compared
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to 1.0%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	for fiscal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	years
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. When interest rates are rising, the full impact of higher interest rates will not immediately be reflected in net income due to the interaction of short- and long-term interest rate changes. During a rising interest rate environment, earnings increase from our short-term investments, and over time increase earnings from our longer-term available-for-sale securities. Earnings from the available-for-sale securities, which as of May&nbsp;31, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	had an average duration of 3.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	years, would not reflect increases in interest rates until the investments are sold or mature and the proceeds are reinvested at higher rates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The amortized cost and fair value of available-for-sale securities that had stated maturities as of May&nbsp;31, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	are shown below by contractual maturity. Expected maturities can differ from contractual maturities because borrowers may have the right to prepay obligations without prepayment penalties.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 1PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:1PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	VRDNs are primarily categorized as due after five years in the table above as the contractual maturities on these securities are typically 20 to 30 years. Although these securities are issued as long-term securities, they are priced and traded as short-term instruments because of the liquidity provided through the tender feature.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Federal Funds rate
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	was raised by 25 basis points in December 2015 and has been in the range of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	0.25%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to 0.50% since then. Previously the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Federal Funds rate
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	had
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	remained at a range of zero to 0.25%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	since December 2008
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Calculating the future effects of changing interest rates involves many factors. These factors include, but are not limited to:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:6PT 0PT 0PT 23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2022;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	daily
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	interest
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	rate changes;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:6PT 0PT 0PT 23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2022;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	seasonal variations in investment balances;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:6PT 0PT 0PT 23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2022;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	actual
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	duration
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of short-term and available-for-sale securities;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:6PT 0PT 0PT 23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2022;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	proportion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of taxable and tax-exempt investments;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:6PT 0PT 0PT 40.5PT;TEXT-INDENT: -16.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2022;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	changes in tax-exempt municipal rates versus taxable investment rates, which are not synchronized or simultaneous;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp; &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:6PT 0PT 0PT 23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:6PT 0PT 0PT 23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2022;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	financial market volatility and the resulting effect on benchmark and other indexing interest rates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Subject to these factors and under normal financial market conditions, a 25-basis-point change in taxable interest rates generally affects our tax-exempt interest rates by approximately 17&nbsp;basis points. Under normal financial market conditions, the impact to earnings from a 25-basis-point change in short-term interest rates would be approximately $3.5 million to $4.0 million, after taxes, for a twelve-month period. Such a basis point change may or may not be tied to changes in the Federal Funds rate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	0
</FONT>

	billion for fiscal 201

</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1.7% and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1.6% as of May&nbsp;31, 201
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and 201
</FONT>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, respectively. The weighted-average yield-to-maturity excludes available-for-sale securities tied to short-term interest rates such as the VRDNs. Assuming a hypothetical increase in longer-term interest rates of 25&nbsp;basis points, the resulting potential decrease in fair value for our portfolio of available-for-sa
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	le securities as of May&nbsp;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, would be in the range of $20.0 million to $25.0 million. Conversely, a corresponding decrease in interest rates would result in a comparable increase in fair value. This hypothetical increase or decrease in the fair value of the portfolio would be recorded as an adjustment to the portfolio&#x2019;s recorded value, with an offsetting amount recorded in stockholders&#x2019; equity. These fluctuations in fair value would have no related or immediate impact on the results of operations, unless any declines in fair value were considered to be other-than-temporary and an impairment loss recognized.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Credit risk:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We are exposed to credit risk in connection with these investments through the possible inability of the borrowers to meet the terms of their bonds. We regularly review our investment portfolios to determine if any investment is other-than-temporarily impaired due to changes in credit risk or other potential valuation concerns. We believe that the investments we held as of May&nbsp;31, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	were not other-than-temporarily impaired. While $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	155
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million of our available-for-sale securities had fair values that were below amortized cost, we believe that it is probable that the principal and interest will be collected in accordance with the contractual terms, and that the unrealized losses of $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	due to changes in interest rates and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	not due to increased credit risk or other valuation concerns. A
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	significant portion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of these securities in an unrealized loss position as of May&nbsp;31, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	held an AA rating or better. We do not intend to sell these investments until the recovery of their amortized cost basis or maturity, and further believe that it is not more-likely-than-not that we will be required to sell these investments prior to that time. Our assessment that an investment is not other-than-temporarily impaired could change in the future due to new developments or changes in our strategies or assumptions related to any particular investment
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We have some credit risk exposure in connection with our purchase of accounts receivable as a means of providing funding to clients in the temporary staffing industry.&nbsp;&nbsp;This credit risk exposure is diversified amongst multiple client arrangements and all such arrangements are regularly reviewed for potential write-off.&nbsp;&nbsp;No single client is material in respect to total accounts receivable, service revenue, or results of operations.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#PAYX-20160531X10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	REPO
</FONT>
<A NAME="PAYX-20160531X10K_HTM_REPORTMANAGEMENTSASSESSMENT">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	RT ON MANAGEMENT&#x2019;S ASSESSMENT OF
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	INTERNAL CONTROL OVER FINANCIAL REPORTING
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Management of Paychex, Inc. (the &#x201C;Company&#x201D;) is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting as such term is defined in Rules&nbsp;13a-15(f) and 15d-15(f) under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. The Company&#x2019;s internal control over financial reporting is designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of the financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Because of its inherent limitations, internal control over financial reporting may not prevent or detect misstatements. Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Management assessed the effectiveness of the Company&#x2019;s internal control over financial reporting as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	May&nbsp;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. In making this assessment, management used the criteria set forth by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission in &#x201C;Internal Control&nbsp;&#x2014; Integrated Framework&#x201D; (2013). Based on our assessment, management determined that the Company maintained effective internal control over financial reporting as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	May&nbsp;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:12PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:23.75PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company&#x2019;s independent registered public accounting firm, PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP, is appointed by the Company&#x2019;s Audit Committee. PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP has audited the Consolidated Financial Statements included in this Annual Report on Form 10-K and the effectiveness of the Company's internal control over financial reporting as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	May&nbsp;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, and as a part of their integrated audit, has issued their report, included herein, on the effectiveness of the Company&#x2019;s internal control over financial reporting.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE;WIDTH: 100.00%;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 1PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:1PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="WIDTH:03.72%;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;PADDING:0PT 0PT 0PT 3.6PT;">
